                                If you do a quick google search for the answer to this question,<B> its pretty difficult to get a straight answer</B>. That’s <I>not</I> because the question can’t be answered – <i>
                                    its because most bloggers seem to think the question is irrelevant.
                                </i>
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                <b>So, they invariably skip straight to explaining about the stages of sleep, and why sleep is important </b>. They actually don’t answer the fundamental question they began with.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <blockquote class="quote"><b>Sleep is a vital component of our biological cycle</b>. It is a period of downtime that allows our body and mind to rest and recuperate.</blockquote>
                            <p></p>
                            <p>
                                <b>When you are asleep, you are experiencing an altered state of consciousness.</b> This is characterised by a distinctly different pattern of the passage of neural activity in the brain, reduced sensory activity, muscle activity, and overall
                                inhibition of all voluntary muscles.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>The typical chemicals, neurotransmitters, and hormones, <b>fluctuate differently during a period of sleep</b>, then they do during a wakeful state.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                <b> The largest physiological changes during sleep are in the brain.</b> The brain uses far less energy and spends the vast majority of the downtime restoring chemical supplies that are vital for sustaining the energy requirements of
                                wakefulness.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>There are also <b>transitionary processes that involve a range of changes in these levels of neurotransmitters</b> that can initiate, or break the cycle of sleep.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>These transitionary processes <b><span style="text-decoration:underline;">cannot</span> be only considered through the lens of a neuroscientific perspective</b> since they are accompanied by experiential events and dependant upon several conscious-state related factors.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <blockquote><b>Recognising the neurological changes</b> that happen in the brain as you attempt to <b>‘fall asleep’</b>, is an <span style="text-decoration:underline;">essential stepping stone</span> for anybody who suffers from insomnia.</blockquote>
                            <p></p>
                            <p>
                                That is why we will delve next into the explanation of everything you need to know regarding <b>sleep cycles</b> and <b>circadian rhythms</b>. <br /><br />
                                Then we will attribute the <b>neurological transitionary events</b>, to the <b>phenomenological events</b> – <i>
                                    the subjective internal
                                    journey that you undergo every time you lay your head down on that pillow.
                                </i>
                            </p>
                            <hr />
                            <p id="B" style="margin-top:-50px;margin-bottom:100px;"></p>
                            <h1>What are sleep cycles?</h1>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><b>Sleep cycle consists of variation of stages of sleep.</b> Most people are usually expected to have <i>between 4 and 6 cycles of sleep every night</i>.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <img src="~/Content/Images/sleepcycles.jpg" />
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                During a sleep cycle your brain will undergo a <b>change in in neurological rhythms and patterns</b> that can be measured using an <b>electroencephalogram</b> –<i> also known as an EEG.</i> The electroencephalogram readings measure variations in in the
                                <b>frequency</b> and the <b>amplitude</b> of neurological activity.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <blockquote class="quote" style="text-align:center; "><b>The EEG readings associated with sleeping patterns account for <span style="text-decoration:underline;">cortical</span> areas of the brain</b>. This consists of the outermost layers of the forebrain.</blockquote>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                <b>Data derived from EEG data indicates that sleep can be divided into 'cycles'</b> -<i> which generally last about 80 to 100 minutes</i>.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                <b>Every sleep cycle can be divided into distinctly unique 'stages'</b> - <i>which last between 10 or 15-minutes.</i>
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <H2 style="background-color:darkorange; color:white;"><strong>AWAKE</strong></H2>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <img src="~/Content/Images/wavesawake.jpg" />
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><b>During a wakefull state the brain is very active.</b> The EEG readings indicate that neurons in the cerebral cortex are firing at a high frequency and in a pattern that can appear random.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>This is because<b> the sensory threshold is lower during a wakefull state</b> -<i> allowing the propegation of action potentials to occur more frequently.</i></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>This is characterised by <b>'noise'</b> on an EEG reading, because the frequency of the cerebral brain activity is quite high – <i>around 15-and 10 Hz</i> </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <blockquote><b>Subjectively</b>, these patterns are experienced as the process of <b>sensing, thinking, and acting</b>.</blockquote>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <H2 style="background-color:darkorange; color:white;"><strong>Stage One</strong></H2>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <img src="~/Content/Images/wavesstage1.jpg" />
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                When you enter that <b>drowsy state</b>... you are drifting in to the the <b>first stage of sleep</b>.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                From the moment your head hits the pillow, under normal circumstances, you will slowly drift into the first stage of sleep where
                                the <b>frequency of cerebral brain activity <span style="text-decoration:underline;">lowers</span> noticeably</b>  – <i>to around 4-8 Hz</i>.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                <B>The amplitude of the cerebral brain activity <span style="text-decoration:underline;">increases</span></B> - <i>to around 50-100 Μv</i>.

                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <h5>Why does the frequency and amplitude change?</h5>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>As you go to sleep <b>neural inhibition <span style="text-decoration:underline;">increases</span></b> - <i>to <b><span style="text-decoration:underline;">reduce</span> the sensitivity</b> of neurons</i>. </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <blockquote class="quote" style="text-align:center;">This <b>reduces your sensitivity</b> to external stimuli and <b>allows internal patterns of neural activation to propagate</b> throughout the brain with <b>less disturbances</b>.</blockquote>
                            <p></p>
                            <p>During wakefulness cortical activity is very high but also considerably chaotic. This is because the waves of activation or shorter, a characteristic of high-frequency readings on a EEG.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <h2 style="background-color:darkorange; color:white;">Stage Two</h2>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <img src="~/Content/Images/wavesstage2.jpg" />
                            @*<p><br /></p>
        <img src="~/Content/Images/sleepspindlesandkcomplex.png" />
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p>
                            <b>The second stage of sleep is much like first stage</b> - <i>the amplitude and frequency of brain activity is similar</i>.
                        </p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p style="background-color:rgba(225,255,240,1);">
                            However, during the second stage there are <b>momentary characteristic fluctuations in brain activity</b>.
                        </p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <div class="container-fluid">
                            <div class="row">
                                <div class="col-md-6" style="padding:5px;">
                                    <div style="border:1px solid black;border-radius:8px;background-color:rgba(255,100,30,1);text-align:center;">
                                        <H5 style="border:none;color:white;"><span style="color:white;">SLEEP SPINDLES</span></H5>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                                <div class="col-md-6" style="padding:5px;">
                                    <div style="border:1px solid black;border-radius:8px;background-color:rgba(255,100,30,1);text-align:center;">
