                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <h5>What are sleep spindles?</h5>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p>
                            <b>A sleep spindle is characterised by a temporarily increased frequency of brain activity</b> – <i>10-15 Hz</i>.
                        </p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p>
                            <b>Sleep spindles occur every few minutes and only last for a few seconds</b> - <i>they are often triggered by external stimuli in the surroundings</i>.
                        </p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p>
                            <b>Learning new things during the day increases the number of sleep spindles during sleep.</b>
                        </p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <blockquote style="text-align:center;">
                            Sleep spindles originate in the <b>thalamic reticular nucleus</b> and are believed to be necessary for <b>memory consolidation</b>.
                        </blockquote>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <h5>What is a K-Complex?</h5>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p><b>A K-Complex will occur <span style="text-decoration:underline;">between</span> sleep spindles</b> -<i> they are characterised by <span style="text-decoration:underline;">fluctuations in the amplitude</span> rather than the <span style="text-decoration:underline;">frequency</span> of brain activity.</i></p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p>
                            <b>They appear to be a calibrative reaction to a sleep spindle</b> -<i> they drown out the <span style="text-decoration:underline;">‘noise’</span> associated with the <b>increased brain activit</b>y caused by sleep spindles.</i>
                        </p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p><b>During wakefulness, the activation threshold of cortical synapses is quite low</b> - <i>this makes them very responsive and effective for processing information</i>.</p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <blockquote style="text-align:center;"><b>Each K-Complex increases the threshold for all neural activity</b> which blocks brain activity between weaker connections – <i>which removes the <b>‘noise’</b></i>.</blockquote>
                        <p></p>
                        <p><b>This <span style="text-decoration:underline;">‘down-state’</span> lasts only for a few seconds. </b>Afterwards, the threshold is reduced again and the cortical activity <b>‘reboots’</b> into a more regular pattern.</p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p>The brain activity promoted by each K-Complex consists of <b>more orderly patterns or cortival activation</b> - <i>this is understood to <b>strengthen neural pathways </b>and assist <b>memory consolidation</b></i>.</p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <h2 style="background-color:darkorange; color:white;">Stage Three</h2>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <img src="~/Content/Images/wavesstage3.jpg" />
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p><b>During the third stage of sleep, the amplitude of cortical activity increases further</b> - <i>up to 100-150 μV</i>. </p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p>The <b>waves of inhibition and excitation</b> accross the cortex become very<b> pronounced</b> - <i>with a frequency of 2-4 Hz</i>.</p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <blockquote class="quote"><b>The most highly integrated neural pathways are being stimulated.</b> This <b>reinforces connections</b> and further consolidates long term memories..</blockquote>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p>
                            <b>Sleep spindles</b> <i>(stage two) </i><b>activate neural connections associated with short term memory</b>. This phenomenon<span style="text-decoration:underline;"> increases the probability</span> of these <b>'weaker'</b> neurons being <b>reinforced</b> during deeper sleep.
                        </p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <h2 style="background-color:darkorange; color:white;">Stage Four</h2>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <img src="~/Content/Images/wavesstage4.jpg" />
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p>The forth stage of sleep is characterised by the<b> highly regular</b> patterns in cortical activation. </p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p><b>The frequency of activation is even lower</b> – <i>about 0.5-2 Hz</i>, and the <b>amplitude increases</b> even more – <i>about 100-200 μV</i>.</p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p>
                            <b> Sleep spindles occur in stages 2 and 3 of sleep.</b> However, during stage 4, they are <b>rare</b>. This allows <b>'proximal activity'</b> - <i>the scientific term for patterns of neural activation</i> - to be
                            undisturbed.
                        </p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p>This results in EEG data that exhibits very distinct <b>‘waves’</b> of neural activation.</p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <blockquote class="quote" style="text-align:center;">This is why stage 4 of sleep is called <b>'slow-wave sleep'.</b></blockquote>
                        <p></p>
                        <p><b>This is the point where you could say the person is ‘totally asleep’.</b><i> It is quite difficult to wake somebody up from this stage of sleep.</i></p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <h2 style="background-color:darkorange; color:white;">Rapid Eye Movement (REM)</h2>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <img src="~/Content/Images/wavesrem.jpg" />
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p>
                            The first four stages are actually termed<b> ‘Non-Rapid Eye Movement’ sleep</b>, or <b>N-REM sleep</b>.
                        </p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p>
                            After stage 4, the cortical activation <b>rapidly cycles <span style="text-decoration:underline;">back</span></b> through stage 3, stage 2, and stage 1, before entering <b>‘Rapid Eye Movement’ sleep</b> -
                            <i>otherwise known as <b>REM sleep</b>.</i>
                        </p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p><b style="background-color:rgba(225,255,240,1);">This reversal happens in under ten minutes</b>.</p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <blockquote style="text-align:center;"> During REM sleep, the<b> frequency</b> and<b> amplitude</b> of cortical activation are <b>close to that of somebody awake.</b></blockquote>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p><b>Individuals are easily awakened from REM sleep.</b></p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p> When you wake up,your brain releases a stimulating neurotransmitter called <b> acetylcholine</b>, increasing the level by up to <b>3000%</b> – <i>this is also true when you enter <b>REM sleep</b></i>.</p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <h5>So why dont I wake up?</h5>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p>
                            Throughout the duration of a sleep cycle, neurons in the <a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0960982219311881" target="_blank"><b>sublateraldorsal nucleus</b></a> <span style="text-decoration:underline;"><b>disrupt nerve signals</b></span> being <b>sent to the body</b>.
                        </p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p><b>Brain areas associated with movement are consistently activated during sleep</b> - this disruption prevents signals being sent to the body.</p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <div style="padding:8px;border:2px dashed white;background-color:rebeccapurple;">
                            <p style="color:white;">
                                From an evolutionary perspective, <b>REM sleep is understood as product of our evolution</b>. Sleeping deeply in <b>shorter periods</b> allows humans <i>(and other creatures that sleep)</i> to <b>reassess the security and the safety of their surroundings</b>.
                            </p>
                        </div>
