                        </div>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <h2 style="background-color:darkorange; color:white;">Homeostatic</h2>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p>This concept forms the basis for the idea of <b>'sleep debt'</b> - <i>the idea that avoiding sleep increases levels of physical and mental exhaustion</i>.</p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p>
                            This idea of <b>requiring balance</b> regarding the<b> regulation</b> of sleeping habits is <b>'homeostatic'</b> in nature.
                        </p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p>
                            <B>The homeostatic control over sleeping patterns</B> is caused by a <span style="text-decoration:underline;">chemical</span> that <span style="text-decoration:underline;">accumulates</span> in the brain during wakefullness - <I><b>Adenosine</b></I>.
                        </p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <blockquote class="quote" style="text-align:center;"><b>Adenosine is the <span style="text-decoration:underline;">metabolite</span></b> <i>(end product)</i> <b>of ATP</b> - <i>the source of cellular energy.</i> </blockquote>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p><b>Adenosine accumulates in the brain due to an insufficient glycogen supply</b> - <i>the supply of glucose must be<b> replenished</b> for the metabolism of <b>ATP</b> energy</i>.</p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p><b style="background-color:rgba(225,255,240,1);">This balance is <span style="text-decoration:underline;">restored</span> during slow-wave sleep.</b></p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <h2 style="background-color:darkorange; color:white;">Allostatic</h2>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p><b>Allostatic processes overpower homeostatic control when the situation calls for a critical response</b> –<i> such as a threatening environment or dangerous situation.</i> </p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <blockquote style="text-align:center;">
                            If a person is hungry, thirsty, or in danger, the homeostatic urge to sleep can be overcome to serve <b>survival-based motives.</b>.
                        </blockquote>
                        <p></p>
                        <p>
                            <b>The primary means of allostatic sleep regulation is hormonal and mediated by neural sensory responses</b>, and substances called <b>neuropeptides</b>, such as <b>orexin</b> – <i>chemical that indicates the brain a state of hunger or thirst.</i>
                        </p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <h2 style="background-color:darkorange; color:white;">Circadian</h2>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <img src="~/Content/Images/circadianrhythms.png" />
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p>
                            <b>Circadian rhythms are a natural process that regulates the timing of sleep</b> and generally the cycle repeats every 24 hours and is synchronised with solar time
                            <a href="https://pubs.niaaa.nih.gov/publications/arh25-2/85-93.htm" target="_blank">[Overview of Circadian Rhythms]</a>.
                        </p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p>There is a region of the brain called the <b>suprachiasmatic nucleus</b> located in the<b> hypothalamus</b>. This nucleus contains <b>thousands of small tightly packed cells</b> that serve the purpose of an<b> internal clock</b> – <i>quite literally</i>.</p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <blockquote style="text-align:center;" class="quote;">
                            <b>The DNA inside these cells produce proteins</b> that<b> inhibit the expression of the DNA gene</b>
                            responsible for producing the protein itself.
                        </blockquote>
                        <p></p>
                        <img src="~/Content/Images/superchiasmaticnucleus.jpg" />
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p>
                            <B>Temporally consistent fluctuations</B> of the levels of this protein in the superchiasmatic nucleus <b>provides people with a perception of time</b> - <i>like a pendulum</i>.
                        </p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <blockquote style="text-align:center;">The suprachiasmatic nucleus appears to be <b>solar synchronised</b> by connections to <b>photoreceptors</b> located in the <b>ganglion cells</b> which transmit information, regarding <b>ambient light</b>, to the brain.</blockquote>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <h5>How does our circadian rhythm tell us when to go to sleep?</h5>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <p>
                            <b>The suprachiasmatic nucleus is connected with neurons in the hypothalamus</b>, which have axons the <b>sympathetic nervous system</b> that contain neurons which <b>promote the secretion of <span style="text-decoration:underline;">melatonin</span></b> from the pineal gland.
                        </p>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <blockquote class="quote" style="text-align:center;"><b><span style="text-decoration:underline;">Melatonin is a hormone</span> that controls multiple physiological processes, <span style="text-decoration:underline;">that together promote sleep.</span></b></blockquote>
                        <p><br /></p>
                        <div style="padding:8px;border:2px dashed white;background-color:rebeccapurple;">
                            <p style="color:white;">
                                In the field of neuroscience, <b>mathematical models are developed to describe and predict neurological phenomena</b>. Detailed mathematical models have been developed that reflect the regulation of circadian rhythms,
                                depending on particular factors. <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17517913/" target="_blank" style="color:lawngreen;">[SOURCE]</a>
                            </p>
                        </div>
