                            <h1 class="ql-align-center">THE STRUCTURE OF THE BRAIN</h1>
                            <p><br /></p>
                             <p><b>There are about <span style="text-decoration:underline;">86 billion</span> neurons in the brain.</b> On average,<b> each neuron is connected with <span style="text-decoration:underline;">10,000</span> other neurons</b>. Each neuron is an information-processing and transmitting element of the nervous system.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <h2>What are neurons?</h2>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><b>There are 3 main types of neurons:</b></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <div class="container-fluid">
                                <div class="row">
                                    <div class="col-md-4" style="padding:5px;">
                                        <div style="border:1px dashed lightgrey; border-radius:10px;padding:10px;background-color:rgba(250,0,0,0.05);margin-bottom:10px;"><p style="text-align:center;"><strong>Sensory Neurons:</strong></p> <br />These <b>receive information</b> from the senses.</div>
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="col-md-4" style="padding:5px;">
                                        <div style="border:1px dashed lightgrey; border-radius:10px;padding:10px;background-color:rgba(20,250,0,0.05);margin-bottom:10px;"><p style="text-align:center;"><strong>Inter-Neurons</strong></p> <br />These <b>connect and communicate</b>, allowing information from sensory neurons to be processed and amalgamated.</div>
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="col-md-4" style="padding:5px;">
                                        <div style="border:1px dashed lightgrey; border-radius:10px;padding:10px;background-color:rgba(0,0,250,0.05);margin-bottom:10px;">
                                            <p style="text-align:center;">
                                                <strong>Motor Neurons</strong>
                                            </p> <br />These <b>transmit impulses to muscle cells</b> as a response to signals from the receive impulses from the spinal cord, or the brain
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>The structure of all neurons is fundamentally similar. They are composed of a <strong>‘soma’</strong>, an<strong> ‘axon’</strong>, and multiple <strong>‘dendrites’</strong>.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <img src="~/Content/Images/neuronaaa.png" />
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <div style="border:1px dashed lightgrey; border-radius:10px;padding:10px;background-color:rgba(250,250,250,0.1);margin-bottom:10px;">
                                <h5>Soma</h5>
                                <p></p>
                                <p><strong>The soma is the main body of the cell</strong>. It contains the neurons nucleus, Golgi apparatus, endoplasmic reticulum and mitochondrion – these are machinery that operate the neurons internal processes.</p>
                            </div><p><br /></p>
                            <div style="border:1px dashed lightgrey; border-radius:10px;padding:10px;background-color:rgba(250,250,250,0.1);margin-bottom:10px;">
                                <h5>Dendrites</h5>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p>
                                    The branch like structures that grow out from the soma are the<strong> dendrites</strong>. The name comes from the Greek term ‘Dendron’ meaning tree – since the dendrites divide into <strong>dendritic branches</strong>, that resemble
                                    tree branches.
                                </p>

                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p>The dendrites serve as recipients for messages from other neurons.</p>
                            </div>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <div style="border:1px dashed lightgrey; border-radius:10px;padding:10px;background-color:rgba(250,250,250,0.1);margin-bottom:10px;">
                                <h5>Axon</h5>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p>The axon extends for a variable distance from the <strong>axon hillock</strong> – the initial protrusion of the axon from the<strong> soma</strong>.</p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p>At the end there is the <strong>terminal bulb</strong> consisting of divisions of <strong>telodendria</strong>, which look quite like dendritic branches.</p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p>At the very end of the telodendria there are <strong>synaptic terminals.</strong></p>
                            </div>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                <span style="background-color:rgba(224,255,240,1);">  <b>Neurons transmit</b> chemical impulses <b>through the axon</b> away from the soma <b>in the direction of the terminal bulb</b>.</span>.
                                <br /><br />The message or signal carried in the axon is called an <strong>action potential.</strong>
                            </p>
                            <hr />
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <h2>What are Supporting cells?</h2>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <blockquote><b>The central nervous system contains more than just neurons.</b> There is also a vast collection of supporting cellular arrangements and <b>structures that protect the network of connections</b> in the brain.</blockquote>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                <b>Neurons do not contain storage facilities for nutrients in sufficient quanitities for their high rate of metabolism.</b> Neurons are specialised cells and require support from other cells.<br /><br />The most important supporting cells are called
                                <strong>glial</strong> cells, or <strong>neuroglia</strong>.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <img src="~/Content/Images/glialcell.jpg" />
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                <i>These cells consistute roughly 85% of all brain cells.</i>
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p style="text-align:center;">
                                <span style="text-decoration:underline;"><b>They serve 4 major purposes:</b></span>
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <div class="container-fluid">
                                <div class="row">
                                    <div class="col-md-6" style="padding:5px;">
                                        <div style="border:1px dashed lightgrey; border-radius:10px;padding:10px;background-color:rgba(40,150,60,1);margin-bottom:10px;min-height:50px;">
                                            <p style="color:white;"><b>1. PHYSICAL SUPPORT FOR NEURONS</b></p>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="col-md-6" style="padding:5px;">
                                        <div style="border:1px dashed lightgrey; border-radius:10px;padding:10px;background-color:rgba(40,150,60,1);margin-bottom:10px;min-height:50px;">
                                            <p style="color:white;"><b>2. REGULATE THE SUPPLY OF NUTRIENTS</b></p>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                                <div class="row">
                                    <div class="col-md-6" style="padding:5px;">
                                        <div style="border:1px dashed lightgrey; border-radius:10px;padding:10px;background-color:rgba(40,150,60,1);margin-bottom:10px;min-height:50px;">
                                            <p style="color:white;"><b>3. PHYSICAL INSULATION FOR AXONS </b></p>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="col-md-6" style="padding:5px;">
                                        <div style="border:1px dashed lightgrey; border-radius:10px;padding:10px;background-color:rgba(40,150,60,1);margin-bottom:10px;min-height:50px;">
                                            <p style="color:white;"><b>4. REMOVE TOXINS AND DEAD CELLS </b></p>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p style="text-align:center;">There are 2 <span style="text-decoration:underline;">main</span> types&nbsp;of glial cells, <strong>astroglia</strong>, and <strong>oligodendroglia.</strong></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <div style="border:1px dashed lightgrey; border-radius:10px;padding:10px;background-color:rgba(250,250,250,0.1);margin-bottom:10px;">
                                <h5>Astroglia</h5>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p>
                                    These are star shaped glial cells and provide supportive structure for neurons.
                                </p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p>
                                    The astroglial cells extract nutrients from cappilaries in the brain. These nutrients support neurons, and the maintain the composition of extra
                                    cellular fluid.
                                </p>
                            </div> <p><br /></p>
                            <div style="border:1px dashed lightgrey; border-radius:10px;padding:10px;background-color:rgba(250,250,250,0.1);margin-bottom:10px;">
                                <h5>Oligodendroglia</h5>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p>These cells provide insulating layers of structural protection around the axons of vulnerable neurons.</p><p><br /></p>
                                <p> Branches extend from the glial cell and wrap around neuron axons, a process called <b>'myelination'</b>.</p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p>
                                    <strong>A single oligodendroglia can support the axons of up to 50 neurons. </strong>
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                <b>Signals can move through myelinated axons quicker</b> since there are fewer gates for chemical transmission. – <i>only present at points between segments of meyelin sheath, called <strong>‘nodes of ranvier’</strong>.</i>

                            </p>
                            <hr />
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <h2>How do neurons fire?</h2>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <img src="~/Content/Images/neuronfiring.jpg" />
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <blockquote class="quote" style="text-align:center;"><strong>Inside the soma there is a <span style="text-decoration:underline;">negative resting potential difference</span>, measured in volts, of -70 millivolts</strong>.</blockquote>
                            <p></p>
                            <p><em>Two important chemicals involved in the regulation and modulation of the potential difference in the neuron</em> are <strong>Potassium (K+)</strong> and <strong>Sodium (Na+)</strong>.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p class="quote">
                                <b>The potential difference in charge between the outside and inside of the neuron</b> is controlled by <b>'protein gates'</b> in the neurons membrane.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <img src="~/Content/Images/membrane.jpg" />
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>When the neuron is in a resting state, the <b>Potassium cannot leave</b>, and <b>Sodium cannot enter</b> the neuron.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>The dendrites receive <strong>excitatory</strong> and <strong>inhibitory</strong> <em>signals from <b>synapses</b> located on the neurons dendrites</em>.</p>
                            <p></p>
                            <div class="container-fluid">
                                <div class="col-md-6" style="text-align:center;padding:10PX;">
                                    <div style="border:1px solid red;">
                                        <h4>EXCITATORY</h4>
                                        <p style="color:red;"><b>+</b></p>
                                        <p><i><span style="text-decoration:underline;">Increases</span> the neurons charge.</i></p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                                <div class="col-md-6" style="text-align:center;padding:10PX;">
                                    <div style="border:1px solid blue;">
                                        <h4>INHIBITORY</h4>
                                        <p style="color:blue;"><b>-</b></p>
                                        <p><i><span style="text-decoration:underline;">Decreases</span> the neurons charge.</i></p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>Each dendrite may recieve an influx of <strong>thousands of positive or negative ions</strong>.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><b>This can lead to a change in the net <em>'charge'</em> of the neuron</b> - <i>which is -70mV at rest.</i></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <img src="~/Content/Images/synapse.jpg" />
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>As the electrochemical charge inside the neuron increases, <strong>there is a <u>threshold potential</u>, at around -55 mV,</strong> where voltage-dependant <strong><i>'Sodium gates'</i></strong> are automatically <b>opened</b>.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                <strong>Sodium ions will naturally diffuse</strong> from the <i>sodium-<b>rich</b> </i> to the <i>sodium-<b>deficient</b> extracellular fluid</i>.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <img src="~/Content/Images/sodiumvoltagedep.jpg" />
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                This causes a rapid and powerful <strong>increase</strong> in the intracellular voltage
                                potential.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <img src="~/Content/Images/actionpotential.png" /> <p><br /></p>
                            <blockquote class="quote" style="text-align:center;">When the potential in the axon hillock reaches the <i style="text-decoration:underline;">‘activation potential’</i>,<b> the neuron fires!</b></blockquote>
                            <p></p>
                            <p>
                                The high concentration of Sodium ions in the soma<b> diffuse towards the axon hillock</b><span style="text-decoration:underline"> (opening more Sodium channels)</span>, <b>and down the axon</b> <span style="text-decoration:underline">(opening more Sodium channels)</span>.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <img src="~/Content/Images/axonpropegation.jpg" />
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><b>The Sodium moves down the axon and increases the electrochemical charge,<b> more Sodium gates open</b></b>. - <i>this phenomenon causes the propegating reaction down the axon.</i></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                This propagation continues on to the <strong>‘terminal buttons’ </strong>at the ends of the telodendria, where <b>
                                    ions
                                    are finally released at the next synapse
                                </b> - <i>to enter the next post-synaptic neuron</i>.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>When the electrochemical charge in a neuron reaches the <strong>activation threshold</strong>, Sodium channels close and Potassium channels open.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><span style="background-color:rgba(225,255,240,1);">Then <b>Potassium ions <span style="text-decoration:underline;">leave</span> the neuron</b> and <i><span style="text-decoration:underline;">lower</span> the neurons electrochemical charge.</i>.</span></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>To remove the excess Sodium ions from the neuron, and reabsorb the Potassium ions back into the neuron, ATP energy must be used.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <blockquote class="quote" style="text-align:center;"> <b>Active transport</b> powers the recalibration of the resting potential using <b>ATP energy</b>.</blockquote>
                            <p></p>
                            <p>
                                <b>This active transport is carried out by the 'Sodium-Potassium pump'.</b> This relys on a sufficient supply of <b>Adenosine Triphosphate (ATP)</b> - <i>produced in the mitochondrion organelles within cells.</i>
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <div style="border-left:3px solid grey; padding-left:10px;">
                                <p>According to the National Library of Medicine, 100g of brain tissue burns through 5.6mg of glucose every minute for the production of ATP.[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3900881/" target="_blank">x</a>]</p>
                            </div>
