                            <p><br /></p>
                            <h2>WHAT IS THE STRUCTURE OF THE BRAIN?</h2>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>Now that we understand how individual neurons communicate, the next important step is to understand the actual <strong>shape</strong> of the brain and how different parts are connected and sequenced.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                The brain, along with the spinal chord, is part of the <strong>‘central nervous system’</strong>. The <strong>‘peripheral nervous system’ </strong>refers to nerve cells in the body that are not part of the spinal chord or brain. The
                                brain itself, is composed of three distinct and very important parts; the <strong>‘hindbrain’</strong>, <strong>‘midbrain’</strong> and <strong>‘forebrain’</strong>.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <img src="~/Content/Images/brainsections.jpg" />
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <div style="padding:5PX;border:1px dotted lightgrey;">
                                <h5>The Hindbrain</h5>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p>The hindbrain is located at the top of the brain stem. The two key parts are the <strong>mylenecephalon</strong>, and the <strong>metencephalon</strong>.</p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <img src="~/Content/Images/hindbrain.png" />
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <h3 style="text-align:center;">Myelencephalon</h3>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p><b>This is the <span style="text-decoration:underline;">lowest</span> portion of the brain and connects the brain to the spinal chord.</b> It contains a single important structure called the <strong>medulla oblongata</strong>.</p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p>
                                    <b> The medulla oblongata connects the higher levels of the brain to the spinal cord</b><em>.</em> Its functions are autonomous and include; controlling ventilation, heart rate, blood pressure and general reflexes such as vomiting, coughing,
                                    sneezing and swallowing.
                                </p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <h3 style="text-align:center;">Metencephalon</h3>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p>This is the upper portion of the hindbrain and consists of two regions, the <strong>pons</strong>, and the <strong>cerebellum</strong>.</p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <div style="padding:10px;border-radius:10px;border:1px dashed grey;">
                                    <p><b>PONS</b></p>
                                    <p></p>
                                    <p>
                                        The pons contains nuclei that relay input from the higher brain regions to the cerebellum, as well as nuclei that deal with sleep, breathing, swallowing, bladder control, homeostasis, taste, eye movements, facial expressions, sensations
                                        and posture. It is primarily a signal director, in a sense – a highly connected relay point.
                                    </p>
                                </div>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <div style="padding:10px;border-radius:10px;border:1px dashed grey;">
                                    <P><B>CEREBELLUM</B></P>
                                    <p></p>
                                    <p>
                                        The cerebellum is primarily for motor function. It does not initiate movements, instead it controls coordination, precise movements, balance, posture and motor learning. On inspection, the cerebellum is much like the cortex, only
                                        smaller, and much more specific in its functionality.
                                    </p>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <div style="padding:5PX;border:1px dotted lightgrey;">
                                <h5>The Midbrain</h5>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p>
                                    The midbrain, also known as the <strong>mesencephalon</strong>, is a small part of the whole brain, sitting on top of the hidndbrain. It is associated with vision, hearing, motor control, sleep regulation, alertness, and homeostatic
                                    temperature regulation.&nbsp;&nbsp;
                                </p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p>The main regions in the midbrain are the <strong>tectum</strong>, and the <strong>tegmentum</strong>.</p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <h3 style="text-align:center;">Tectum</h3>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p>The tectum is at the back and is associated with auditory and visual reactive reflexes. <strong>It contains two pairs of colliculi, superior and inferior.</strong></p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>The <strong>superior colliculi</strong> process some visual information, aids the cross over of several fibers of the optic nerve and coordinates head and saccadic eye movements.</li>
                                    <li>The <strong>inferior colliculi</strong> process certain auditory information. It is involved in filtering and separating sounds to create distinctions between them.</li>
                                </ul>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <h3 style="text-align:center;">Tegmentum</h3>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p>
                                    This refers to a group of structures within the tectum. This area contain several nuclei, including the <strong>reticular formation,</strong> the <strong>periaqueductal gray matter</strong>, the <strong>red nucleus</strong>, and the
                                    <strong>substantia nigra</strong>.
                                </p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <div style="padding:10px;border-radius:10px;border:1px dashed grey;">
                                    <p><b>The reticular formation</b></p>
                                    <p><br /></p>
                                    <p>
                                        Roughly a hundred nuclei create this web of interconnected neurons with a range of complex integrative processes that receives information and projects messages wthough axons to the cerebral cortex, thalamus, and spinal chord. It is
                                        implicated in the control of sleeping patterns, arousal, attention, and movements.
                                    </p>
                                </div>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <div style="padding:10px;border-radius:10px;border:1px dashed grey;">
                                    <h6>The periaqueductal gray matter</h6>
                                    <p><br /></p>
                                    <p>This consists of the cell bodies of neurons which surround the cerebral aqueduct. These neurons contain networks that form the basis of low-level instinctive behaviours.</p>
                                </div><p><br /></p>
                                      <div style="padding:10px;border-radius:10px;border:1px dashed grey;">
                                          <h6>The red nucleus</h6>
                                          <p><br /></p>
                                          <p>This contains a collection of axons that deliver motor information from the cerebral cortex and cerebellum, to the spinal chord.</p>
                                      </div><p><br /></p>
                                            <div style="padding:10px;border-radius:10px;border:1px dashed grey;">
                                                <h6>The substantia nigra</h6>
                                                <p><br /></p>
                                                <p>The ‘substantia nigra’ runs through the center of the mid brain, and finishes behind the pons. It is associated with the reward mechanism in the brain and it part of a much larger structure called the <strong>basal ganglia</strong>.</p>
                                            </div></div><p><br /></p>
                            <h5>The Forebrain</h5>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>The forebrain is the largest part of the brain. It has two main parts, the <strong>‘diencephalon’</strong> and the <strong>‘telencephalon’</strong>, or <strong>‘cerebrum’</strong>.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <h3>Diencephalon</h3>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>The diencephalon is home to two main substructure regions; the <strong>thalamus</strong>, and the <strong>hypothalamus</strong>. The thalamus is illustrated below, on its own. It sits, as a pair, in the center of the brain.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <h6>Thalamus</h6>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>The thalamus is another relay station, but with such a central position, it is one of the most vital.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>Neural activity is relayed between subcortical areas of the brain, and the cerebral cortex, part of the telencephalon.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                Every sensory system, aside from the olfactory system (smell), has a dedicated portion of the thalamus that relays its signals to the cerebral cortex. For instance, retinal cells sense a particular wavelength of light, that activates
                                its sensory neuron, which sends a propagation of activation down the optical nerve to the other side of the brain’s thalamus.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>Due to the hyper connectivity, the thalamus has a role to play in many things, motor control, perception, learning, reacting, sleep and wakefulness, and many more functions.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <h6>Hypothalamus</h6>
                            <p>This sits in front and slightly below the thalamus. It is a small but important structure. It is highly associated with the autonomous nervous system, and survival behaviours.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>The hypothalamus is attached to the pituitary gland – the most important hormone releasing gland in the brain. The release of hormones from the hypothalamus controls the realease of hormones from the pituitary gland.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <h3>Telencephalon</h3>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                This consists of three major regions, each divided though the centre of the brain into two hemispheres. The <strong>basal ganglia </strong>and the<strong> limbic system</strong>, are two subcortical regions, covered by the
                                <strong>cerebral cortex</strong>.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <h6>Basal Ganglia</h6>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                Sitting either side of the thalamus is the <strong>‘putamen’ </strong>and the <strong>‘caudate’</strong> . These are two major components of the basal ganglia. The <strong>caudate</strong> receives information from the cerebral cortex
                                and via the putamen, this signal is sent to the <strong>globus pallidus, </strong>the third region of the basal ganglia, and the substantia nigra, in the midbrain.
                            </p>
                            <p></p>
                            <p>
                                The substantia nigra also passes though the <strong>‘basal ganglia’</strong>. Its function relates to reward and learning. The globus pallidus is slightly different. This region outputs to the thalamus with ‘inhibitory’ signals. This
                                has the effect of slowing down decisions and thinking that involves the thalamus.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <h6>Limbic System</h6>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>This region is known to be associated with motivation, emotion, and memory. It consists of the <strong>limbic cortex</strong>, the <strong>hippocampus</strong>, and the <strong>amygdala</strong>.</p>
                            <p>Amygdala</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                The <strong>amygdala</strong> receives information from the cortex and projects this to the tail of the caudate, the underside of the thalamus, the hypothalamus, and various other parts of the brain. The amygdala is heavily involved
                                with decision making, and emotional responses, such as fear, anxiety and aggression.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>Hippocampus</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>The ‘hippocampus’ and ‘striatum’ are the other main parts of the telencephalon. As shown below.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>&nbsp;Limbic Cortex</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>The limbic cortex closely resembles a basic version of the cerebral cortex.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <h3>Cerebral Cortex</h3>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <h1>THE PROCESS OF PERCEPTION</h1>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                My research tackled this idea directly. My study was based on a mathematical model called the ‘Maximum Likelihood Estimate’, or MLE, introduced by Thomas Bayes, a mathematician, and first published by Pierre-Simon Laplace in 1812.
                                Bayesian statistics is concerned with the dynamic relationship between probability and prior knowledge.&nbsp;When Bayesian statistics is used to model human perception and choices it is referred to as Bayes’ inference rule.&nbsp;An
                                important aspect of Bayes’ inference rule is the likelihood function and the incorporation of prior assumptions when estimating a percept.&nbsp;
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                The model describes the integration of incongruent normally distributed data. A normal distribution has a mean, and a reliability, as shown in the diagram below. Two distributions with an equal reliability can be integrated by the
                                average of their means. However, if the reliability weighting differs between the two sets of data, then the total average will account for this by moving closer to the more reliable data.
                            </p>
                            <p>&nbsp;</p>
                            <p>
                                According to our research data, and many other papers and experiments, in many circumstances, the MLE model can be used to accurately predict perceptual estimates of incongruent sensory input. There are a few conditions that must be
                                accounted for not to mention the experimental limitations of extracting accurate data from participants.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                The ‘Maximum Likelihood Estimate’ (MLE) model represents an optimal method for predicting perceptual estimates for stimuli presented to multiple senses.&nbsp;When sensory information is merged this can be either sensory ‘integration’ or
                                ‘combination’. Sensory integration and combination are defined by Ernst et al. (2004) as processes used to create a precise single percept in the brain.&nbsp;The important difference is that the MLE rule only applies to sensory
                                ‘integration’; when the information derived from each modality is associated with the same features of a stimulus (Ernst et al., 2004).
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                Predicting perceptual estimates for sensory integration, using the MLE model, is dependent upon perceived spatial and temporal coincidence (Mancini et al., 2010). In simple language, the object that is being sensed, by both senses, must
                                ‘appear’ to be in the same place, at the same time, for somebody to believe that both senses originate from the same object. Simon-Dack et al., (2009) provided additional evidence for this finding using fMRI, indicating that populations
                                of haptic-related neurons are activated by visual stimuli – in this case, laser light – when the light corresponds spatially and temporally with the hands.&nbsp;
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                Another condition for perceptual predictions, via the MLE model, is the actual discrepancy between the unimodal sensory information. If you see a train and hear a tram, then you will most likely guess that it is indeed a train. But why
                                is that? Misceo &amp; Taylor (2011) found evidence that, in specific conditions, sensory integration does not occur and the estimate is strongly biased towards the more appropriate modality.&nbsp;Centvelzen et al., (2009) found that the
                                integrations of visual and auditory estimations of speed closely match MLE predictions and perceptions are only disregarded when there is a greater than 3:1 difference in reliability weightings. We trust certain senses more than others.
                                Humans have remarkable visual capabilities. This extra confidence in our vision is called sensory dominance. When the proximal activity in the brain is processing a vision of a train, the variance of uncertainty is much less. This means
                                that the object associated areas of the brain that are most activated are more clearly those that we associate with imagery of trains. We never mistake a train for a bus, or a bike, or a teaspoon!
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                Now, what if you saw a train, and heard a firework? Surely your brain would not integrate these sensory inputs, even if they occurred in the same place, at the same time. Ernst et al. (2004) queried whether there was a level of
                                perceptual discrepancy that elicited robust behaviour where the less appropriate modalities percept is vetoed.&nbsp;This was shown to be the case in research by Reuschel et al. (2001). They found that the MLE rule did not predict the
                                integration of visual and proprioceptive information when determining absolute path trajectories, left or right. The diagram below is an example of the multisensory normal distributions that would require sensory selection over
                                integration.
                            </p>
                            <p>&nbsp;</p>
                            <p>
                                Moving swiftly back to the train analogy, have you ever been sitting in the window seat on a train, waiting at the station, when another train is waiting on the tracks next to your train. Your train begins to move, unexpectedly! A few
                                seconds later you realise that it is the other train that is departing, not yours. This is a good example of a perceptual discrepancy that can only be resolved by sensory veto. Your visual sense it telling you that you are moving. Your
                                proprioception tells you; you are not moving. The visual sense is dominant and almost always right, but it can’t be right, because you always feel the movement… Your brain searches for some visual evidence that you are indeed not moving
                                and when the new visual information is received the integration occurs and the discrepancy is resolved.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                For the MLE model to apply, the discrepancy between redundant stimuli must be within a range for which the net mean weighted estimate retains a greater reliability than the most appropriate modality. Welch and Warren (1980) suggested
                                that inter-sensory discrepancies may provoke an immediate calibration response to derive an accurate perception.&nbsp;When required to provide a perceptual estimate, the brain must converge incongruent information from different sensory
                                modalities to select the most likely percept.&nbsp;The perception of a stimulus presented through a single sensory modality causes a propagation of neural activity that for which the resolve is a gaussian distribution. This is
                                characterised by uncertainty centred around a mean average. For two, equally reliable senses, the discrepancy is resolved by assuming the mean of both averages to be true. This is illustrated below.
                            </p>
                            <p>&nbsp;</p>
                            <p>
                                If you were to look at a chair, you would see a chair. However, the neural activation would not only activate the portion of your brain that is associated with that exact chair, but also, many other chairs, perhaps even furniture, or
                                anything else that has a strong association with the chair, in your brain. The final perception you experience will be the object that has the highest association with all of the activated areas. This is the average mean of the normal
                                distribution of activation.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                Stevenson et al. (2009) demonstrated that super-additivity could explain how integration enhances certainty according to the MLE rule.&nbsp;The superposition of the neural activation converging from multiple sources increases the rate
                                of firing in the integration zone.&nbsp;The estimation is therefore derived from the multimodal neuron populations exhibiting the greatest rate of firing. The specific area of neural activation is associated with the mean percept which
                                deviates according to reliability weightings or variances, as predicted by MLE.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                When the object is perceived via multiple senses, if the information is incongruent, but not so much as to lead to sensory selection, integration occurs. This is because the probability weighting of the mean is greater, as shown below,
                                than that of either unimodal estimate.
                            </p>
                            <p>&nbsp;</p>
                            <p>
                                If, for instance, the discrepancy was greater, then the probability weighting of the integrated mean would be less than that of each unimodal estimate. This would mean the brain would have to choose which sense to believe over the
                                other. This is sensory selection. Studies have found that as the discrepancy between unimodal stimuli increases, the frequency of participants integrated estimates decreases as sensory dominance takes over. Participants are then more
                                likely to choose one, over the other.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                In the graph below, two highly incongruent stimuli provoke two highly discrepant perceptual estimates. The integrated mean average of the estimates yields a result that is not associated with either. The brain does not conduct math to
                                yield results, instead, the organic nature of the superposition of neural activation yields results that can be modelled with maths. I have illustrated the normal distribution for the integrated perception, but in reality, this never
                                occurs! The brain simply assumes one of the unimodal perceptions to be true.
                            </p>
                            <p>&nbsp;</p>
                            <p>
                                This integration happens after the inter-sensory processing stage, and occurs in specific regions of the brain. Stevenson et al. (2009) found the position of this area of convergence is dependent on the modalities being measured. For
                                example, certain broader regions such as the Parahippocampal Place Area (PPA) and the Retrosplenial Cortex (RSC) are important areas implicated in the study of visual and haptic (touch) sensory integration (Wolbers et al.,
                                2011).&nbsp;Subsequent research using Functional Magnetic Resonance Imaging (fMRI) studies have found these specific areas to be responsively activated during simultaneous visual and haptic exploration (Wolbers et al.,
                                2011).&nbsp;Specifically, visual and haptic perceptions appear to converge within the fusiform-gyrus (Stevenson et al., 2009).&nbsp;This is not the case when senses are stimulated on their own. When presented with visual-haptic distal
                                stimuli, the rate of neuron firing in the fusiform-gyrus is greater than when exploring the stimuli within a single modality (Stevenson et al., 2009).
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                The position of convergence for neural patterns is not limited to those described above.&nbsp;For instance, the output from the neural convergence derived from visual and vestibular cues regarding motion and direction are integrated
                                near-optimally by populations of neurons in the dorsal medial superior temporal area (Angelaki et al., 2011).
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                Some research goes even further, considering senses that usually are not considered senses. Scientifically, we do not have only five senses. We have so many more. They are mostly subtle, in comparison, but without them, we would
                                struggle with day to day tasks. A good example of one of these senses is proprioception. This is the awareness of the position and movement of the body. This sense is found in the vestibular system that includes the parts of the inner
                                ear and the brain that help control balance and eye movements. Without this sense, problems occur with vision, hearing, balance, vertigo and dizziness, among other issues. Reichel et al., (2010) found optimal integration, reflecting the
                                MLE model assumptions, occurs between vision and proprioception when estimating particular trajectories of movement.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                Research has shown that the brain integrates these perceptions in accordance with the MLE model. The MLE model predicts that incongruences are resolved by taking into account reliabilities and relative weightings of each modality (Ernst
                                &amp; Banks, 2002).&nbsp;As a result, this model has been established as an effective method for predicting perceptual estimates. Studies have shown that the model can even predict lower level inter-sensory perceptual estimates. Any
                                attempt to measure perceptual estimates must be done so with an effective and specific experimental procedure.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                A study by Deneve, Latham &amp; Pouget (1999) found that when inner cortical circuitry is activated, the pattern of activation elicited by populations of neurons appears to function closely to that of an ‘ideal observer’ and they could
                                predict the shape of the propagation of activation by using the MLE model.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                In other words, the MLE model can describe the integration of neural activation propagation patterns, which from now on I will refer to as proximal activity, before the positions of multi-sensory convergence. For example, the primary
                                visual cortex projects to the dorsal visual area which appears to have a strong association with the estimation of depth, location, and motion. Research by Dövencioğlu et al., (2013) presented multiple incongruent visual depth cues
                                simultaneously to participants. The depth cues were designed to specifically target binocular disparity and the participants assumptions regarding shading variations associated with depth. The results concluded that the MLE rule
                                effectively describes the resolution of in-congruent interpretations and the participants’ estimates.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                The reason this is important is because it demonstrates that there are stages of processing that occur before a final perception is created. Perceptual integration is not something that occurs only in, for instance, the fusiform Gyrus.
                                Perceptual integration is something that transcends much deeper into the very fabric of our neural structure. It explains the normal distribution of activity arising from any single sensory input. The various activation must resolve
                                hundreds of incongruences on the way though any part of the cortex.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                In non-neuroscientific terms, perception is not something that occurs in a specific part of the brain. Instead, it is a process of increasing understanding. The immediate experience is processed and the perception becomes clearer and
                                clearer. Imagine a window that is so dirty, nothing can be see through it. Perception is the process of cleaning the window. Every wipe with a cloth reveals more until the window is completely clean, and you can see what is on the other
                                side.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                When you look at a chair, if time stood still the moment after, your perception of the chair would be unclear. You would not be sure what the object actually is. A moment later, your brain would identify the edges and corners. Another
