                            <h1>WHY SHOULD YOU START MEDITATING?</h1>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><b style="background-color:rgba( 224, 255, 240,1); padding:2px;">This is the real question most people can’t find a straight answer to.</b></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                Religions have interpretations of meditation that <b>over-emphasize the experience</b> in ways that can <b>estrange</b> and <b>alienate</b> people.
                                The <b>'other-worldly references'</b> in the language is often perceived as<b> condescending to those who do not practice meditation.</b>
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>People talk about the state of <b>‘oneness’</b>, <b>‘euphoria’</b>, <b>‘enlightenment’</b>, and other various <i>altered states of consciousness.</i></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <img src="~/Content/Images/MED1111.jpg" />
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>Although <b>there is sufficient anecdotal evidence to verify these claims, through a scientifically significant ‘more likely than not’ deduction</b>; these results are usually the result of <b>years of meditative practice</b>. The ideas can seem <B>alien</B> to those who have little experience of the practice.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><b><i>The reason you should not let yourself be discouraged</i></b>, is that <i>meditation is first and foremost a <b>brain training exercise</b></i> that increases your ability to <b>control your thinking and behavior in everyday life</b>.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <div style="padding:10px; background-color:rgba(200,200,200,0.1);border-radius:20px;border:1px solid rgba(200,200,200,0.5);">
                                <h5><strong>What is the dog on a leash analogy?</strong></h5>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p><i><b>The best analogy</b> to describe the process of meditation</i> is to <b>imagine you are walking your dog in the park</b>.</p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p><b>The dog represents your thoughts</b> – <i>and this dog… is <span style="text-decoration:underline;"><b>CRAZY!</b></span></i></p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <img src="~/Content/Images/CRAZYDOG.jpg" />
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p>
                                    <B>The dog is running wild all over the place </B><I>sniffing everything</I> and anything, running over to other people and <I>
                                        jumping on them
                                    </I>, and even <I>chasing the ducks into the lake and getting soaking wet.</I>
                                </p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p style="text-align:center;"><B>You have no control over this dog.</B> </p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p style="text-align:center;"><b style="text-decoration:underline;">Just like you have no control over your mind.</b></p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p>
                                    <i>You may <b style="text-decoration:underline;">think</b> your actions are always justified</i>
                                    by the complex mechanism that is your thoughts – <b>just like the dog is justifying its own actions</b> when it's scurrying around, getting wet and shaking itself dry all over that couple sunbathing nearby.
                                </p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p style="text-align:center;"><b>But you are not the dog. </b>You are the owner of the dog.</p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p>In this analogy, the <b>dog is in control of your thoughts</b> – like your <b>brain is in control of your thoughts</b>.</p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p style="text-align:center;"><b>But you are not the brain. </b>You are the owner of the brain.</p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <blockquote class="quote" style="text-align:center;"><b>Meditation is like applying a leash to the dog’s collar.</b></blockquote>
                                <p></p>
                                <p><b>Now that you have control</b> over the leash <b>you can slowly reel in the dog</b> and <b>train it to stop and sit.</b></p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <img src="~/Content/Images/GOODDOG.jpg" />
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p>Every time you meditate, <b>you are reeling in your passage of thoughts</b> to <i>stop them from getting carried away in their own story.</i></p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <blockquote>Soon you learn <b>not to identify as the brain</b>, and instead <b>identify as a spiritual being</b> with access to a brain, a body, and a world, to experience.</blockquote>
