                            <p id="L1" style="margin-top:-50px;margin-bottom:100px;"></p>
                            <h2 class="ql-align-center"><strong>Focus and Attention Meditation</strong></h2>
                            <p class="ql-align-center"><br /></p>
                            <p><b>This is the most important form of meditation to master.</b> It is the fundamental starting point for any beginner, and can be practiced at any level of experience.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <h5>
                                Remember: Clearing the mind of all thought that is peripheral to that of the chosen focus <span style="text-decoration:underline;color:goldenrod;">
                                    is the goal of the
                                    exercise
                                </span>. The exercise itself is the <span style="text-decoration:underline;color:orangered">process of realising when the focus deviates</span>, and <span style="text-decoration:underline;color:limegreen;">realigning</span> it to the chosen focus.
                            </h5>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                The more practice you gain from<b> consistent</b> and <b>regular</b> <i>focus and attention meditation</i>, the more <b>subtle</b>
                                the deviations will become - <i>but there will certainly be distractions</i>. Meditation is the <b>'process'</b> of <b>'recognising'</b> these distractions - <i>however subtle they may be.</i>
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <div style="border-radius:20px;border:1px dashed rgba(40,50,60,0.3);background-color:rgba(255,240,225,1);padding:10px;">
                                <h5>7 Step Guide To Focus And Attention Meditation</h5><p><br /></p>
                                <p>
                                    <b>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;Find a suitable position to remain in for the duration of the exercise.</b> More advanced techniques will be more specific about your posture and form. At this stage, it is more effective to be comfortable and in a safe place.
                                </p>
                                <img src="~/Content/Images/med222.jpg" style="width:300px;margin:0 auto;border:none;" />
                                <p><b>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;Choose your focus! Many people choose a mantra. </b>There is misunderstanding all over the world about the importance of paying special people to give you your perfect mantra – but you can work this out on your own.</p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <div style="background-color:white;border-radius:10px;padding:10px;border:1px dashed rgba(40,50,60,0.3);">
                                    <p>
                                        Choose either a foreign, ancient word for which the meaning has significance to you. Ensure that the word is not one associated with anything else you can remember. It must be a new word in your mind – one that you can refine and
                                        develop the meaning for in your own way.
                                    </p>
                                    <h5>Here are some examples of mantras.</h5>
                                    <details>
                                        <summary><h4 style="display:inline-block;">Aum</h4></summary>
                                        <p><i>Pronounced 'Ohm'. A simple mantra considered to be the sound of the universe. It means to 'Be' or to 'become'.</i></p>
                                    </details>
                                    <details>
                                        <summary><h4 style="display:inline-block;">Om Namah Shivaya</h4></summary>
                                        <p><i>Translates to 'I bow to Shiva'. Shiva represents the higher self. Each of the 6 syllables has a special meaning, so the mantra can be translated as 'I, Earth, Water, Fire, Air, Energy'.</i></p>
                                    </details>
                                    <details>
                                        <summary><h4 style="display:inline-block;">I am that I am</h4></summary>
                                        <p><i>Drawing in the breath you acknowledge your presence and everything that you are, and breathing out, you align your self with everything that is. </i></p>
                                    </details>
                                    <details>
                                        <summary><h4 style="display:inline-block;">Aah-ham-pree-mah</h4></summary>
                                        <p><i>Translates to 'I am divine love'. It is a mantra to be repeated 108 times to align your soul with divine love.</i></p>
                                    </details>
                                    <details>
                                        <summary><h4 style="display:inline-block;">Om Mani Padme Hum</h4></summary>
                                        <p><i>To be considered with the meaning of 'Om' aligning with the sound of the universe, 'Ma' distinguishing your needs, 'Ni' removing your desires, 'Pad' freeing you from prejudice, 'Me' releases your possesiveness, and 'Hum' removing your hatred.</i></p>
                                    </details>
                                    <details>
                                        <summary><h4 style="display:inline-block;">I am full of light.</h4></summary>
                                        <p><i>Clear your spirit from darkness and evil and teach your self to emanate goodness and light.</i></p>
                                    </details>
                                    <details>
                                        <summary><h4 style="display:inline-block;">Lumen de Lumine</h4></summary>
                                        <p><i>Clean your aura and absorb brightness and energy. Liberate yourself from darkness to be protected from darkness, ignorance, and evil.</i></p>
                                    </details>
                                    <details>
                                        <summary><h4 style="display:inline-block;">Love is in everything. Love is everything.</h4></summary>
                                        <p><i>Plant the seed in your mind for realigning your passion and love for the world. See the world through a new lense - one that is filled with compassion.</i></p>
                                    </details>
                                </div>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p>
                                    <b>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;Keep your mantra secret! Your mantra is going to be used every time you meditate. </b>By sharing information with others, you are weakening the association of your mantra with your higher self. It should not be connected to
                                    the web of neurons devoted to communication. It needs to be pure and remain a deeply significant symbol of your spiritual oneness and security.
                                </p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p>
                                    <b>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;Breath in and out, slowly – chanting your mantra with each breath. </b>Some people choose to chant it out loud, but I highly recommend you chant your mantra in your head. Devote all your attention to the mantra, not the
                                    breath.
                                </p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <img src="~/Content/Images/medmantra2.jpg" />
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p><b>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;Let the mantra consume any thoughts, sensations, ideals, epiphanies, images, sounds, emotions, or otherwise.</b> Let your mantra soak it up as the sound of the mantra (in your head) becomes louder and louder.</p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p><b>6.&nbsp;&nbsp;When your mind is utterly focused on only the mantra, let the sound fade away</b> and let the mind rest in complete peace for the duration of the meditation.</p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p><b>7.&nbsp;&nbsp;If thoughts, emotions, or sensations return, rekindle the chant of your mantra getting louder until it has consumed your focus,</b> before returning to a silent mind.</p>
                            </div><p><br />This might sound quite difficult to do but if you read it over a couple of times, do some research, and find a mantra that works for you<i> (the shorter the better)</i><b> you will find this exercise quite simple.</b></p>

