            <h2 class="ql-align-center">WHAT IS THE SKIN?</h2>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>
                It might come as a surprise to some of you that the <strong>skin is not just the surface </strong>that most of us worry so much about<strong>. It is a multi-layered organ that encapsulates our entire body.</strong> As such, it is the
                largest organ of the body.
            </p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <img src="~/Content/Images/skinderm.jpg" />
            <p class="ql-align-center"><br /></p>
            <p>The skin is comprised of <strong>three distinct layers</strong> that each serves a very specialised purpose:</p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><strong>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Epidermis</strong></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><em><b style="background-color:yellow;">This is the outside surface of the skin</b> that we see all the time. It is the <b>first layer of protection</b> our bodies have against debris, dirt, and microbes.</em></p>
            <p><br /><em>It is also a <b>waterproof barrier</b> and contains special cells called <b>melanocytes</b> – the source of the melanin responsible for our skin tone.</em></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><strong>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Dermis</strong></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><em><b style="background-color:yellow;">This layer is directly beneath the epidermis.</b> It contains the strong connective tissue that cushions the body from stress and strain. </em></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <ul>
                <li><em>The upper portion is the papillary dermis that is filled with thin and randomly arranged fibres.</em></li>
            </ul>
            <p><br /></p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <em>The lower portion is the dermal papillae and its ridge-like structure is responsible for the patterns in your fingerprints. These ridges increase its surface area allowing more blood flow to reach the surrounding cells.</em>
                </li>
            </ul>
            <p><em>&nbsp;</em></p>
            <p><strong>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Hypodermis</strong></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>
                <em>
                    <b style="background-color:yellow;"> The is the lowest layer of the skin</b> and is sometimes referred to as <b>subcutaneous tissue</b>.
                    Within the hypodermis, loose connective <b>collagen fibres connect the tissue to the dermis and the deeper bodily tissues</b>. The bulk of the layer
                    is composed of <b>subcutaneous fat</b>.
                </em>
            </p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <blockquote><b>Among all the layers there are</b> capillaries delivering blood to all our skin cells, hair follicle roots, cutaneous nerves, and lymphatic vessels for transporting waste.</blockquote>
            <p></p>
            <p><b style="background-color:yellow;">Subcutaneous fat is widely distributed across the body</b> and can help with thermoregulation, protective padding, and an on-demand energy reserve.</p>
            <hr />

            <p id="B" style="margin-top:-50px;margin-bottom:100px;"></p>
            <h2 class="ql-align-center">WHAT IS THE FUNCTION OF THE SKIN?</h2>

            <p><br /></p>
            <img src="~/Content/Images/skin1.jpg" />

            <p class="ql-align-center"><br /></p>
            <blockquote class="quote"><b>As the largest organ of the human body</b>, it is no surprise that the skin performs many different functions.</blockquote>
            <p></p>
            <p>
                It is the <b>combination of these abilities</b> within our skin that <b>protect us</b> from the external world,
                allow us to <b>learn</b> about our environment, and <b>feel</b> our way around, while also serving its purpose to <b>keep our body alive</b>.
            </p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><strong>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;Protection.</strong></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>
                <em>
                    Our skin is first and foremost a <b>protective barrier</b> from the elements our body is exposed to every day.
                    Pathogens that come into contact with the skin are quickly <b>broken down by the lysozymes in our sweat.</b>
                </em>
            </p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><strong>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;Sensations.</strong></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><em>There are many <b>different types of nerve endings</b> in the skin that respond to different sensations – temperature, pressure, injuries.</em></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><strong>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;Temperature regulation.</strong></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>
                <em>
                    <b style="background-color:yellow;">The skin has access to a large quantity of blood flow</b>.
                    Through <b>vaso-dilation</b> and <b>vaso-constriction</b>, the blood flow through the skin is regulated. This allows the body to lose heat through the skin at a controlled rate.
                </em>
            </p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><strong>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;Fluid retention, excretion, and water resistance.</strong></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>
                <em>
                    The dry outer layers of the skin provide a <b>variably impermeable barrier</b> for fluids.
                    This allows our body to <b>preserve essential nutrients</b> when exposed to water. Additionally, it allows our body to control the release and
                    <b>evaporation of bodily fluids</b> from the skin.
                </em>
            </p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><strong>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;Vitamin D synthesis</strong></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>
                <em>
                    <span style="background-color:yellow;">In the presence of sunlight, <b>vitamin D can be photo-chemically synthesised in the skin</b></span>. Vitamin D is essential for promoting calcium absorption in the intestines. Maintaining a balance between calcium and phosphate levels is
                    essential for bone formation and densification.
                </em>
            </p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><strong>6.&nbsp;&nbsp;Absorption.</strong></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>
                <em>
                    Our blood delivers oxygen to cells in our bodies so they can survive. But this is not true fo the outermost layer of your skin.
                    <b>The skin cells that are less than half of a millimetre deep actually absorb oxygen directly from the air</b>
                    around them.
                </em>
            </p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>
                <em>The skin absorbs oxygen, but that’s not all it can absorb. <b>There are many substances that the skin will readily absorb</b> if it meets the correct criteria; such as medicines administered through the skin, such as a nicotine patch.</em>
            </p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><strong>7.&nbsp;&nbsp;Attractiveness</strong></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>
                <em>
                    The most widely know function and purpose of the skin, is to serve as <b>an aesthetical asset</b>.
                    The colour, texture, and homogeneity of the skin are <b>recognised as features of a healthy individual</b>. <br />
                </em><br />
            </p>
            <blockquote><em>The skin serves as a <b>communicative representation of your inner state</b> including not only <b>overall health</b> but also <b>emotional mood</b> and <b>psychological stability</b>.</em></blockquote>


            <p id="C" style="margin-top:-50px;margin-bottom:100px;"></p>
            <h2 class="ql-align-center">IS THE SKIN THE SAME ALL OVER THE BODY?</h2>

            <p><br /></p>
            <img src="~/Content/Images/skinsame.jpg" />
            <p class="ql-align-center"><br /></p>
            <p><b style="background-color:yellow;">The skin takes on different characteristics all over the body.</b> The requirements and functions that your skin can adapt are largely dependent on positional variances.</p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><strong>What about subcutaneous fat?</strong></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>
                The most noticeable difference is the <b>variability of the thickness of the skin throughout the body</b>.
                This is due to the presence of <b>subcutaneous fats</b>, which are present to a lesser degree in the face and the chest.
            </p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>The extra padding from <b>subcutaneous fat provides more protection</b> in regions of the body that are subject to more wear and tear.</p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><strong>What are skin appendages?</strong></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>The areas of your body where the skin is thinner contain more <b>appendages</b>. Appendages refer to structures such as hair follicles, sweat glands, oil glands, and other porous zones for fluid retention and excretion.</p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><strong>What is the significance of skin appendages?</strong></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>
                When these structures are more densely populated within the skin, <b>this helps the skin rejuvenate quicker and easier</b>. Skin appendages are more often located in areas that are subject to less wear and tear – the best example being facial
                skin.
            </p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <blockquote>
                The greater density of <b>oil and moisture reservoirs</b> in facial skin plays a <b>significant role in rejuvenation</b>.<br /><br />
                As a result, <b>facial skin is more tolerant of injury and heals much faster</b> than the skin on other areas of the body.
            </blockquote>
            <hr />

            <p id="D" style="margin-top:-50px;margin-bottom:100px;"></p>
            <h2 class="ql-align-center">WHAT IS SKIN FLORA?</h2>

            <p><br /></p>
            <img src="~/Content/Images/skin2.jpg" />
            <p class="ql-align-center"><br /></p>
            <p>
                <b style="background-color:yellow;"> The skin supports an entire ecosystem of microbes. </b>
                This is not to be considered a negative property that should be taken care of. <br /><br />
            </p><blockquote class="quote">
                In fact, <b>no amount of cleansing and moisturizing will remove the vast collection of facial flora</b> present
                in the skin.
            </blockquote>
            <p></p>
            <p>The skin is home to <b>thousands of species of bacteria</b> and they rest in <b>three distinctly different areas of skin </b>that are identified by their attributes:</p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><b>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;Dry areas</b></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>
                <em>
                    <b>These are located near skin folds</b> such as between the <b>toes and fingers, or the edges of the nostrils and ears</b>.
                    These areas are home to a small selection of bacteria, most commonly; <b><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proteobacteria">b-Proteobacteria</a></b> and <b><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flavobacteriales">Flavobacteriales</a></b>.
                </em>
            </p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><b>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;Moist areas</b></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>
                <em>
                    <b>These areas are dominated by <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corynebacterium">Corynebacteria</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Staphylococcus">Staphylococci</a>.</b> Anywhere on the body that is prone to the accumulation of moisture,
                    such as the <b>underarms.</b>
                </em>
            </p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><b>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;Sebaceous areas</b></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><em><b>These areas are home to the majority of species of skin flora.</b> These areas are located all over the body to some degree. </em></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>In many cases, <b style="background-color:yellow;">the distance between a ‘dry-zone’ and a ‘moist-zone’ can be a matter of centimetres</b>, yet the populations of skin flora species are dramatically different.</p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>
                The presence of these bacterial populations is <b>not something that is considered a problem</b>.
                The numbers, and ratios, of skin flora, are <b style="background-color:yellow;">in a state of balance.</b>
            </p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>
                The microbiome refers to the “<a href="https://www.the-scientist.com/commentary/ome-sweet-omics---a-genealogical-treasury-of-words-54889" target="_blank">ecological communities of commensal, symbiotic and pathogenic microorganisms</a>“.
                The balance is crucial for a healthy immune system and the overall homeostasis of the body.
            </p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <blockquote><strong>The number of skin flora present on a single square inch of the body is, on average, roughly 50 million!</strong></blockquote>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><span style="background-color:yellow;">If you removed them <b>all</b> and <b>rolled them up into a ball</b> they would only be the <b>size of a pea</b></span>!</p>
