            <p id="E" style="margin-top:-50px;margin-bottom:100px;"></p>
            <h2 class="ql-align-center">WHAT IS SKIN PERMEABILITY?</h2>

            <p><br /></p>
            <img src="~/Content/Images/skin66.PNG" />
            <p class="ql-align-center"><br /></p>
            <p>
                <b>Permeability refers to the ability to allow the diffusion of molecules through a membrane.</b>
                The skin's permeability can be compared to a <b>sieve</b>. The <b>greater</b> the permeability, the <b>more</b> substances can pass through.
                The <b>lesser</b> the
                permeability, the more substances are <b>rejected</b>.
            </p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>
                <b>The skin is a semi-permeable surface.</b> As previously mentioned, <span style="background-color:yellow;">the skin readily allows oxygen to diffuse into its outermost cells</span> – but oxygen is a fundamental element and very tiny in comparison to most substances that come into
                contact with the skin.
            </p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>
                Research into epidermal medicines has found that <span style="background-color:yellow;"><b>nano-particles less than 40 nano-meters in diameter can successfully pass through the epidermis</b></span> of the skin. One of the weaker more permeable areas is in the region around hair follicles.
            </p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><strong>Why is it important for the skin to be impermeable?</strong></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>
                The diffusion of substance into the skin means  <b>allowing those substances into the body.</b> Our skin is our primary layer of defence from substances that are potentially harmful toxins that must be prevented from coming into contact with
                internal tissues.
            </p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><strong>What can reduce skin impermeability?</strong></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>
                The skin is designed to allow in elemental particles, <b>particular vitamins and minerals, and sunlight</b>. It is a careful balance that, when disturbed, can allow various microbes or external surface debris into the body that can lead to an
                <b>imbalance in skin flora, or even infection, or adverse reactions to poisonous substances.</b>
            </p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <blockquote>The <b>reduce the effectiveness</b> of the skin's delicate foreign substance barrier, the skin needs to be damaged or eroded.</blockquote>
            <p></p>
            <p>This can be caused by:</p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Tape stripping</strong></li>
            </ul>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>
                <em>
                    The act of <b>applying an adhesive based tape to the surface of the skin</b> and removing it can <b>lift the top layer of the epidermis</b> away. The top layers of the epidermis are usually comprised of dead skin cells. However, removing this
                    dead skin layer exposes the fresh layers and <b>reduces their protection from alien substances</b>.
                </em>
            </p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Abrasion</strong></li>
            </ul>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>
                <em>
                    Using a <b>rough</b> or <b>graded material</b> to rub away the top layer of the epidermis leads to the same problem as tape stripping.
                    Additionally,<b> it can damage the healthy under-layer of the epidermis</b>.
                </em>
            </p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Chemical Solutions</strong></li>
            </ul>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>
                <em>
                    Various chemicals are used, not only in scientific medical research but also in <b>everyday skincare products</b>,
                    to <b>increase the permeability of the skin</b>. Some chemicals<b> dissolve organic materials</b> such as dead skin cells and others are
                    <b>acid-based</b> which allows the top layers of the skin to be washed away.
                </em>
            </p>
            <hr />
            <p id="F" style="margin-top:-50px;margin-bottom:100px;"></p>
