            <h2>7.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Moisturise</h2>

            <p><br /></p>
            <img src="~/Content/Images/skin12.jpg" />  <p><br /></p>
            <p>Sometimes it can feel like a chore to remember to moisturise your skin every day, <b>but it’s certainly not a waste of time.</b></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <blockquote><b>Moisturising can keep your skin smooth, clear, and feel lighter and softer</b>, not to mention the cumulative anti-ageing benefits that come from a long-term effective skin-care regime.</blockquote>
            <hr />
            <p><strong>Why do I need to moisturise?</strong></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><b style="background-color:yellow;">Dead skin cells are shed more often on the face and below the neck than anywhere else on the body.</b> This leaves these areas much more prone to dryness and flaking.</p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>
                <b>Moisturisers work by replacing lost fluids on the surface cells of the stratum corneum.</b> <i>This is the top layer of the skin which consists of various dead cells</i>. However, these dead cells are not at a stage where they are ready to be
                shed. <b>They can still absorb water like and other cells.</b>
            </p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <blockquote class="quote">For skin to look fresh, smooth, and at its best, the cells in the stratum corneum should contain around 20-30% water.</blockquote>
            <p></p>
            <p>
                <b>If the stratum corneum layer dehydrates to a water content of less than 10%, this can cause the skin to become flaky and chapped.</b> <span style="background-color:yellow;">
                    Properly hydrated corneocytes, the dead cells in the stratum corneum, will expand in volume causing them
                    to become <b>more tightly packed</b>
                </span> – <i>this is what gives facial skin the smooth and healthy look</i>.
            </p>
            <hr />
            <p><strong>What makes a good moisturiser?</strong></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><b>Moisturisers are designed to hydrate your skin</b> and the science behind their ability to perform this function effectively is not common knowledge. <b>Here are four important components for any moisturiser:</b></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <div style="background-color:rgba(200,200,200,0.1);padding:5px;">
                <p style="text-align:center;"><strong>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;Water</strong></p>
                <p><br /></p>
                <p><strong>Moisturisers contain water.</strong> This water is the essential ingredient for hydrating the skin. However, the oils in the skin repel water, and it remains on the surface, where it quickly evaporates.</p>
            </div><p><br /></p>
            <div style="background-color:rgba(200,200,200,0.1);padding:5px;">
                <p style="text-align:center;">2.&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Occlusives</strong></p>
                <p><br /></p>
                <p>
                    <strong>This is why moisturisers also contain Occlusives. </strong>These are usually oils. Applying a layer of hydrating water to the skin, and topping it up with a layer of oil will trap the water in-between, forcing it to be absorbed
                    into the skin.
                </p>
            </div>
            <p><br /></p>
            <blockquote>Without the presence of an <b>occlusive component</b>, the product is probably not a <b>‘moisturiser’</b> – <b>it is a ‘cream’</b>.</blockquote>
            <p></p>
            <div style="background-color:rgba(200,200,200,0.1);padding:5px;">
                <p style="text-align:center;">3.&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Humectants</strong></p>
                <p><br /></p>
                <p>
                    <strong>Where occlusives are present in a moisturiser, they usually also contain Humectants.</strong> These are chemicals, such as glycerine, or honey, that draw moisture up to the surface of the skin from the lower layers, which are
                    more easily replenished by your circulation.
                </p>
            </div>
            <p><br /></p>
            <blockquote>If a moisturiser contains <b>humectants</b>,<b> without oils</b>, then the moisture that is drawn up from the lower layers can reach the stratum corneum and evaporate, <b>leaving you with even more dry skin</b>.</blockquote>
            <p></p>
            <div style="background-color:rgba(200,200,200,0.1);padding:5px;">
                <p style="text-align:center;">4.&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Emollients</strong></p>
                <p><br /></p>
                <p><strong>Emollients are chemicals that can make the skin feel smoother</strong> by normalising the surface texture of the skin. Most occlusives and humectants double up as emollients.</p>
            </div><p><br /></p>
            <p>A good moisturiser should contain these <b>four components</b> in a natural and dermatologically safe form.</p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>
                Since the skin benefits greatly from the presence of certain vitamins and minerals, <b>using moisturisers that contain added vitamin A, C and/or E can be beneficial for keeping your skin healthier</b> through nourishment, as well as hydration.
            </p>
            <hr />
            <div style="padding:10px;border:2px dotted orange;background-color:rgba(255,200,50,0.05);text-align:center;">
                <p><strong>How can I make my own moisturiser?</strong></p>
                <p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>
                <p>
                    <i>
                        The components listed above, that are <b>vital for an effective moisturiser</b>, <b>can be sourced from a range of different chemicals and substances</b>. Commercial products will use laboratory chemicals to provide the occlusives, humectants, and
                        emollients.
                    </i>
                </p>
                <p><br /></p>
                <p>Even though they are always dermatologically tested, some of us would rather use more natural ingredients on our skin. <b>Here is my favourite method that works every time.</b></p>
                <p><br /></p>
                <p>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;<b>Pour a ¼ cup of water into a jar.</b></p>
                <p>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;<b>For the occlusive ingredient I prefer to use three tablespoons of melted coconut oil.</b></p>
                <p>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;<b>For the humectant I use about three tablespoons of manuka honey.</b> <br /><i>You can also use a cheaper grade or glycerine (if you can find it)</i>.</p>
                <p>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;<b>For the emollient, I use two tablespoons of Argon oil</b>,<br /> <i>but you can also use shea butter, jojoba oil or cocoa butter</i>.</p>
            </div>
