            <h2>8.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Visit Saunas</h2>
            <p><br /></p>
            <img src="~/Content/Images/skinsauna.png" />
            <p class="ql-align-center"><br /></p>
            <p>All of the skin-care remedies that we have discussed up to this point all have one thing in common – <b>they increase the production of collagen.</b></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <blockquote>Collagen is the most abundant protein in your body and is <b>a vital component of the connective tissues in your skin</b>.</blockquote>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><b style="background-color:yellow;">Boosting the levels or production of collagen will contribute to healthier and more vibrant skin.</b></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><b>As we age, the production of collagen declines</b>, reducing the elasticity of the skin and causing it to fall burden to the effects of gravity and movement causing sagging, wrinkling, stretching, and folding.</p>
            <hr />
            <p><strong>How can visiting a sauna increase collagen production?</strong></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <div style="background-color:rgba(200,200,200,0.1);padding:5px;">
                <p><b style="background-color:yellow;">Visiting a hot sauna will raise your bodies core temperature.</b></p>
                <p><br /></p>
                <ul style="padding:0;">
                    <li>The homeostatic reaction that occurs to maintain your healthy bodily temperature involves <b>vasodilation</b>.</li>
                    <li><b>Vasodilation opens up the capillaries</b> to allow more blood flow to the extremities and the surface of the skin.</li>
                    <li>The excess heat in the blood is transferred out of the body <b>through your sweat</b>.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>
                The <b>heightened blood flow increases the nutrient availabilityto your epidermal cells</b>  and the healthy exchange of fluids in your sweat glands <i>creates a fresher and more mineral rich environment to stimulate the production of collagen.</i>
            </p>
            <hr />
            <p><strong>Are there any other benefits?</strong></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>Aside from the obvious point that <b style="padding:5px; background-color:aquamarine;">saunas are the most relaxing places to lounge in and feel amazing</b>, there are other skin-related benefits!</p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><b>The heavy sweating you experience in a sauna is a flow of fluids flushing through your pores and glands, removing toxins, dirt and impurities.</b> This can be beneficial for the prevention of acne, blackheads, whiteheads, and pimples.</p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><b>By stimulating your sweat glands your skin begins to produce more sebum </b>– <i>a substance that helps maintain your skins hydration leaving you with a healthy glow every time you leave the sauna.</i></p>
            <div style="width:100%; text-align:center;">
                <br />
                <iframe style="width:90%;margin:0 auto;" height="150" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/Bg4wH-74ir0?start=2" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>
            </div>
