                                </b>
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><b>There are so many ways to whiten your teeth</b>, some of them are more effective, or more expensive, or invasive. Some methods simply do not work.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><span style="background-color:yellow;">The best method to whiten your teeth is to keep them healthy</span>. They may never be the brightest shade of white, but they will certainly stay strong, hard, and pretty white, for a lifetime.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><b>Unhealthy teeth are the result of improper oral hygiene</b>. The science behind the degradation of perfectly healthy teeth <i>all points towards dietary choices and oral hygiene routines</i>.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <hr />
                            <p id="SECOND" style="margin-top:-50px;margin-bottom:100px;"></p>
                            <div style="padding:20PX;border:3PX solid RGBA(40,50,60,1);"><h2 class="ql-align-center">WHAT CAUSES UNHEALTHY TEETH?</h2></div>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <div style="border:1px solid rgba(40,50,60,0.05); background-color:rgba(100,100,100,0.05); padding:10px;text-align:center;">
                                <p><b>Each of your teeth are composed of:</b></p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <h5>A root</h5>
                                <p>This <i>holds the tooth in position</i> and <b>maintains the overall structure of the tooth</b>.&nbsp;&nbsp;Within the root there is the <b>root canal</b>, containing the nerves and blood vessels that pass through.</p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <h5>Pulp</h5>
                                <p>This is where the <b>blood vessels</b> and <b>nerves</b> reside.</p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <h5>Dentin</h5>
                                <p>This is the <b>yellowy-colored protective mineral interior</b> of the tooth.</p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <h5>Enamel</h5>
                                <p>The <b>visible exterior</b> of the tooth.</p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                            </div>

                            <p><br /></p>
                            <img style="width:50%;border:none;" src="~/Content/Images/teethtooth.png" />
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><b>The visible part of your teeth is the enamel</b>. <span style="background-color:yellow;">Enamel is the hardest substance in the human body and contains the highest percentage of minerals than any other tissue</span>.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>Despite its strength, <i>once the enamel is formed <b>it is separated</b> from the blood flow</i> and nervous system. <b>This means the body cannot repair tooth enamel</b>. This is why the enamel is built to last a lifetime.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                A basic unit of enamel is called an <b>enamel rod</b>. An enamel rod is a tiny building block made of a <b>tightly packed mass of hydroxyapatite crystals arranged in a crystalline form</b>. Substances with a crystalline form are famously incredible
                                hard due to their dense structure.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>Unfortunately, according to famous historic physicist Thomas Young, <b>substances that are ‘hard’ are often brittle</b>, and this is true for enamel as well.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <blockquote class="quote">Wear and tear can produce fractures and loss of enamel over time.</blockquote>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <hr />
                            <p id="seconda" style="margin-top:-50px;margin-bottom:100px;"></p>
                            <p style="text-align:center;"><strong>What is demineralization?</strong></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><b>The crystalline substance that forms the enamel on your teeth is subject to all the stresses and strains of your diet</b> and the chemicals that they are exposed to.&nbsp;<b>As such they are susceptible to ‘demineralization’</b>.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><i>Demineralization occurs when the <b>enamel is exposed to acids</b></i>.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><b>Demineralization is the most salient cause of tooth decay</b> and it affects everybody to some degree.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>Highly acidic substances will, indeed, be highly corrosive for your enamel. The level of acidity in our food and drink is of an acceptable level, but <b>over time, even slightly acidic substances can have cumulative effects</b>.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><span style="background-color:yellow;">Tooth enamel begins to deteriorate at a PH level of 5.5</span>. This is roughly the PH of a <b>milky coffee</b>. The is the lowest level of acidity that will begin to demineralize the enamel coating on your teeth.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <hr />
                            <p id="secondb" style="margin-top:-50px;margin-bottom:100px;"></p>
                            <p style="text-align:center;"><strong>How does sugar cause demineralization?</strong></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>Fermentable carbohydrates, such as sugar, fizzy drinks, fruit juice, and sweets, <b>all produce this effect</b>.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>The sugar coats the surface of the mouth and interacts with the healthy bacteria in the mouth. <b>This causes the healthy bacteria to produce lactic acid</b> which, in turn, initiates the <b>demineralization process.</b></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <div style="text-align:center;">
                                <iframe style="width:80%;" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/BE_h4bTdcdQ" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>
                            </div>
                            <hr />
                            <p id="secondc" style="margin-top:-50px;margin-bottom:100px;"></p>
                            <p style="text-align:center;"><strong>What is the danger of demineralization?</strong></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>When demineralization occurs, following an acidic oral environment, <i>the enamel is left vulnerable to bacterial invasion for roughly 30 minutes.</i></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><em>Here is a pair of images taken with a scanning electron microscope showing:</em></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <img src="~/Content/Images/teethelectron.jpg" />
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>As you can see, <i>the temporary demineralization caused by the exposure to an acidic environment</i> (comparable with a soft drink) leaves the surface of the to enamel <b>very impaired</b>.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                During this time frame, <b>many different types of unhealthy bacteria can sink into the enamel of the teeth</b>. The most notable bacterium is <b>Streptococcus mutans</b> – this bacterium is naturally present in the human oral microbiota, along with
                                several other species.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>Many of these bacteria thrive in higher acidity and <b>produce lactic acid when exposed to sugars</b>, glucose, and other fermented carbohydrates,<b> leading to a further increase in acidity</b>.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><i>The consistent creation of enamel demineralizing climates allows the bacterium to <b>sink deeper into the enamel</b></i>, <span style="background-color:yellow;">causing dental decay and eventual toothaches and ultimately, the loss of teeth</span>.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <hr />
                            <p id="secondd" style="margin-top:-50px;margin-bottom:100px;"></p>
                            <p style="text-align:center;"><strong>What is dental plaque?</strong></p>
                            <p><br /></p>

                            <img src="~/Content/Images/teethplaque.jpg" />
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p class="ql-align-center"><br /></p>
                            <p><b>Dental plaque is a collection of bacteria that attaches and grows on the enamel.</b> &nbsp;</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <blockquote style="text-align:center;">It forms a layer all over the enamel – a colorless sticky deposit.</blockquote>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>
                                In normal circumstances, the use of our teeth for breaking down abrasive foods <b>will remove the initial deposits of dental plaque before they become an issue</b>. However, there are parts of the teeth coated with a dental plaque that
                                remain <b>undisturbed</b> during the process of eating.
                            </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>These are commonly between the teeth, along the gum line, and sometimes even below the gumline.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>The build-up of dental plaque means an <b>increasing mass of bacteria that produces acid</b> which leads to the destruction of the tooth enamel.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <hr />
                            <p id="seconde" style="margin-top:-50px;margin-bottom:100px;"></p>
                            <p style="text-align:center;"><strong>What is dental calculus?</strong></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <img src="~/Content/Images/teethcalculus.jpg" />
                            <p class="ql-align-center"><br /></p>
                            <p><span style="background-color:yellow;">Dental calculus is a form of hardened dental plaque.</span> The seam between the tooth and the surrounding gums is called the <b>gingivae</b>.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><b>Precipitation of minerals from the fluid in the gingival crevices</b> and saliva <b>kills the bacterial cells</b> in the dental plaque <b>forming a layer of calculus</b>.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>This layer of calculus is simply <b>a mineralised layer of dead bacteria</b>, but the new surface lends itself to <b>further accumulation of plaque</b>.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>The process repeats and the layers build causing a <span style="background-color:yellow;">protruding yellow-colored calculus called <b>‘tartar’</b></span>.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>This layer interferes with the <b>lining of the gums</b> around the teeth leading to <b><i>bleeding, bad breath, receding gums, and inflamed gingivae</i></b>.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <blockquote><b>Whitened teeth do not mean healthy teeth</b>. Plaque, calculus, demineralization, and wear and tear cannot be resolved or cured with teeth whitening procedures.</blockquote>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><b>Healthy teeth are the result of consistent and effective oral hygiene</b>. An efficient oral care routine is the safest, quickest, and most dependable method of achieving long-term dental health.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
