                            <h2>3.&nbsp;Floss when you can, but not too often.</h2>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>Did you know that nearly <span style="background-color:yellow;">40% of the surfaces of your teeth are ‘<b>interdental</b>’</span>? Meaning, they are areas between your teeth that are inaccessible for a regular toothbrush, or even an electric toothbrush.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>A good technique to target these areas, and protect them from a build-up of bacteria and plaque, is <b>flossing</b>.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <img src="~/Content/Images/dentalfloss.jpg" style="width:50%;" />
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>According to the American Dental Association, <b>flossing can remove up to 80% of plaque in these areas.</b></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>Since the plaque in these areas can be physically connected to gingival plaque located between the gums and the surface of the teeth, <b>flossing can also help remove plaque in these associated regions as well.</b></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>As with brushing your teeth, flossing also has a method which if executed incorrectly, can be ineffective and even damaging – <b>especially for your gums.</b></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><strong><span style="background-color:yellow;"><b>The correct procedure is as follows:</b></span></strong></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;Use a piece of floss about <b>30cm long.</b></p>
                            <p>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;Wrap the floss between your <b>two middle fingers</b></p>
                            <p class="ql-align-center"><br /></p>
                            <img style="width:40%;" src="~/Content/Images/floss1.png" />
                            <p class="ql-align-center"><br /></p>
                            <p>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;Grasp the floss on each side <b>between your thumbs and index fingers</b>.</p>
                            <p class="ql-align-center"><br /></p>
                            <img style="width:40%;" src="~/Content/Images/floss2.png" />
                            <p class="ql-align-center"><br /></p>
                            <blockquote>Leave about an inch of floss in between</blockquote>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;Slide the floss <b>between your teeth and up to the gum</b>.</p>
                            <p class="ql-align-center"><br /></p>
                            <img style="width:40%;" src="~/Content/Images/floss3.png" />
                            <p class="ql-align-center"><br /></p>
                            <p>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;Curve the floss to the side and <b>rub it up and down to clean the side of the first tooth</b>.</p>
                            <p class="ql-align-center"><br /></p>
                            <img style="width:40%;" src="~/Content/Images/floss3b.png" />
                            <p class="ql-align-center"><br /></p>
                            <p>6.&nbsp;&nbsp;Curve the floss <b>in the opposite direction</b> to clean the side of the other tooth.</p>
                            <p class="ql-align-center"><br /></p>
                            <img style="width:40%;" src="~/Content/Images/floss4.png" />
                            <p class="ql-align-center"><br /></p>
                            <p>7.&nbsp;&nbsp;<b>Repeat the process between all your teeth</b>.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><span style="background-color:yellow;">Make sure you do not slide the floss back and forth (in and out of your mouth) since this may damage your gums</span>.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>Some experts suggest that <b>oral irrigation is a safer and more effective</b> method to clean your teeth and gums, rather than flossing.</p>
