                            <H2><span class="fa fa-cutlery">  </span>  LUNCH</H2>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><B>Lunch is usually the toughest meal to get right</B>, because it needs to be planned.Most of us are out and about or at work during lunch and its not always easy to eat a healthy option.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>This is why <B>lunch should be simple preparation</B>. You shouldn't prepare too many meals in advance, since they become increasingly less appetising!</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>Instead, prepare your lunch right after breakfast. At the very least, your lunch should have:</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <ul>
                                <li><b>Root Vegetables:</b> Garlic / Onions / Carrots / Potatoes</li>
                                <li><b>Leafy Greens:</b> Kale / Spinach / Bok Choy / Lettuces / Herbs</li>
                                <li><b>Legumes:</b>  Beans / Chickpeas / Lentils / Peas</li>
                                <li><b>Fruits:</b> Bananas / Oranges / Apples / Cucumbers</li>
                                <li><b>Nuts and Seeds:</b> Pine nuts / almonds / walnuts / pecans / sunflower seeds / pumpskin seeds / cashews.</li>
                            </ul>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><B>SO WHATS THE SECRET?</B></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <blockquote style="text-align:center;">EAT MORE SALADS</blockquote>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <img src="~/Content/Images/saladlunch.jpg" style="border:none;" />
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <h5>HOW DO I MAKE A SALAD?</h5>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><b>Throw leaves of Watercress, Radicchio, Oak leaf, Endive, and Gem lettuce into a salad bowl</b>.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><b>Add some fresh Basil</b>, Parsley, Mint or any other leafy herbs that you like.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><b>Mix in some thinly sliced root vegetables</b> such as carrot, cucumber, beetroot, or celery. </p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><b>Top with a light mixture of fruit, and nuts and seeds</b>, for sweetness, texture and protein. Maybe even croutons.</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p>The base doesnt have to be leafy greens, it can be anything you like, quinoa, brown rice, tomato and cucumber slices...</p>
                            <p><br /></p>
