                                    </p>
                                    <h2>WHAT IS SELF HYPNOSIS?</h2>
                                    <p><br /></p>
                                    <img src="~/Content/Images/watchaa.jpg" />
                                    <p><br /></p>
                                    <p>Self-hypnosis is the result of a <strong>self-induced hypnotic state.</strong></p>
                                    <p><br /></p>
                                    <p>A self-hypnotic state is a state of mind that increases <strong>self-suggestibility</strong>. &nbsp;</p>
                                    <p><br /></p>
                                    <p>There is no hoax or trick involved in self-hypnosis. It is not a magical imaginary power that some people have and others don’t. It is simply a process of thinking that can be very clearly explained, understood, and carried out.</p>
                                    <p><br /></p>
                                    <div style="border:5px solid rgba(40,50,60,1);">
                                        <div style="background-color:rgba(40,50,60,1); color:white;padding:5px;"><p style="color:white;"><strong>There are three main types of self-hypnosis:</strong></p></div>
                                        <p><br /></p>
                                        <div style="padding:10px;">
                                            <ul>
                                                <li><strong>Concentration Hypnosis:</strong></li>
                                            </ul>
                                            <p><br /></p>
                                            <p><em>This is similar to the most fundamental method of transcendental meditation. The idea is to focus exclusively on an idea central to the motivation of the self-hypnosis, like a mantra.</em></p>
                                            <p><br /></p>
                                            <ul>
                                                <li><strong>Inclusive Hypnosis:</strong></li>
                                            </ul>
                                            <p><br /></p>
                                            <p><em>This is what I like to call zero-focus meditation. This is more or less the opposite of meditation and can be best described by a relaxed control over the flow and passage of thoughts.</em></p>
                                            <p><br /></p>
                                            <ul>
                                                <li><strong>Visual Hypnosis</strong></li>
                                            </ul>
                                            <p><br /></p>
                                            <p><em>This is similar to a combination of the two described above. The hypnosis exercise is entirely visual and takes place in the mind eye. Instead of repeating a suggestive phrase, you imagine specific outcomes in vivid detail.</em></p>
                                        </div>
                                    </div><p><br /></p>
                                    <p>Unlike meditation, <strong>these types of self-hypnosis encourage activation of the cortex</strong> – the higher thinking region of the brain.</p>
                                    <p><br /></p>
