            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>The body needs particular substances to grow, repair, and to extract energy. Any foods that do this for the body will contain a particular spectrum of nutrients.</p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>There are 5 major classes of <b>macro-nutrients</b>:</p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Carbohydrates</li>
                <li>Fats</li>
                <li>Proteins</li>
                <li>Fibre</li>
                <li>Water</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>And 2 major classes of <b>micro-nutrients</b>:</p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Vitamins</li>
                <li>Minerals</li>
            </ul>
            <p><br> </p>
            <p>An effective diet is one that delivers these nutrients with <b>minimal consequence</b>.</p>
            <p><br> </p>
            <p>Studies have shown that a <strong>whole-grain plant-based diet</strong> does exactly that.</p><p><br /></p><p> The underlying principles allow for a more ethical approach to the problem of food, in addition to the proven health benefits.</p>
            <p>
                <br />
            </p>
            <p>
                <img src="~/Content/Images/Food_Pyramid_Vegetarian_Food_Guide-11.jpg" />
            </p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>According to the Harvard Medical Schools' healthy eating plate, the healthiest diet consists of mostly vegetables, fruit and whole-grains, healthy fats, and healthy proteins. </p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Do you eat enough fruit and vegetables?</strong>
            </p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>About <b>90% of the population do not eat the recommended portion of vegetables</b>, which should account for a third of our diet. Fruit should account for 20% of our diet and this level is rarely met. </p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>
                <b>A whole-grain plant-based diet requires these foods to be the center of our diet</b>. A variety of fruit and vegetables is more nutrient-rich and vitamin-stuffed than anything else you could eat.
            </p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Do you over-indulge in animal-based food products?</strong>
            </p>
            <p><br></p>
            <p>
                Animals flesh contains a dense package of nutrients with little fibre. An ideal food when resources are depleted. In modern society, we have so many healthier choices, alternatives, substitutes - we certainly shouldn't be eating meat everyday!
            </p>
            <p><br></p>
            <p>Animal-based food products have an obvious healthy consequence - <b>saturated fats!</b></p><p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p> Healthy fats are <b>unsaturated</b> and found mainly in plant-based foods and oils. Yet, many fats consume too many saturated fats - most commonly found in animal sources of food, such as red meat, poultry, and full-fat dairy products. </p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Are you watching your cholesterol?</strong>
            </p>
            <p><br></p>
            <p>Cholesterol is that sticky substance in your blood. Your body needs a safe level of cholesterol to function normally.</p>
            <p><br></p>
            <p>Too much cholesterol can cause fatty deposits to build up on the inside of your blood vessels leading to an increased rist of <b>heart disease</b>.</p>
            <p><br></p>
            <p>Your level of cholesterol will rise significantly with a diet consisting of eggs, cheese, processed meats, steak, fast food, or fried foods. </p>

