            </p>
            <H5>
                SUSTAINABLE FISH FARMS ARE FINE THOUGH, RIGHT?
            </H5>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>
                Fish farming is prone to many of the same problems as regular farming. There is waste, pesticides, antibiotics, parasites, and diseases. In the UK, around 70 million farmed fish are slaghtered each year. Disease claims 10-30% of the populations before they reach this stage.
            </p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>
                As if that wasn't a compeeling enough reason to stop supporting fish farming, lets consider the environmental impact. The waste product from these 'high-density' poulations of farmed fish builds up in the region. This depletes the water of oxygen creating 'deadzones' in the ecosystem, and in some cases, polluted drinking water.
            </p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>
                With the rising sea temperatures, many sources of farmed fish will be forced to increase their use of antibiotic drugs to ensure high survival rates. These can affect surrounding ecology and possibly remain inside the food in small quantities.
            </p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <H5>
                THE OCEANS ARE SO VAST... THEY MUST BE FINE?
            </H5>
            <p><br /></p>
            <blockquote>The seafood industry is causing an oceanic environmental disaster!</blockquote>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>Switching from farmed livestock to a pescatarian diet is so problematic for our oceans. Large fish populations have been reduced by over 90% due to the unsustainable methods.</p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>Harvesting this sheer quantity of fish is nigh-on impossible for even the largest sustainable fish farms. If you decide to eat fish then it is likely you are funding the destruction of our oceanic environments, which contain 99% of the living space on the entire planet – where 80% of all life on earth resides. </p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>Fishing also introduces competition with the more majestic species on our planet. Blue whales were abundant in nearly all the oceans on earth – until 100 years ago! The population reduced from 303,000 to around 15,000. That’s a serious reduction. The oceans are becoming more desolate as we squeeze the life out of them.</p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <blockquote class="quote" style="text-align:center;">“For years we thought that the oceans were so vast and the inhabitants so infinitely numerous that nothing we could do could have an effect upon them. ... The oceans are under threat now as never before in human history.” <br /><br /><b>David Attenborough, 2017.</b></blockquote>

