            <h2 class="ql-align-center"><span style="color: windowtext;">1.&nbsp;WHAT IS CORONAVIRUS?</span></h2>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>Coronavirus is a single-stranded RNA virus that is approximately 50-200 nanometers in diameter. It consists of a spherical membrane, known as an ‘envelope’, containing a single RNA genome. The envelope contains a few proteins, the most recognizable being the ‘Spike’ Glycoprotein. This is the protein that is responsible for allowing the virus to ‘hook on’ and fuse with the membrane of a host cell.</p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p><strong>How does it infect a cell?</strong></p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>When the virus has attached itself to the target cell, it sinks inside with the membrane of the target cell forming a bubble around it. Then, a protein breaking enzyme in the virus slices its spike protein open, breaking the membrane bubble – the last barrier of defense for the target cell. </p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>The virus releases RNA into the target cell nucleus causing it to create copies of the RNA and produce an increasing level of corrupted mRNA. The mRNA is transported to the cell organelles where new copies of the virus are manufactured. </p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>The membrane proteins begin to coat the surface of the target cell and the RNA is transported from the nucleus. A collection of RNA exits the target cell surrounded by a bubble of its victims' corrupted membrane. </p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p><strong>How does the virus spread?</strong></p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>The virus predominantly spreads between people via small water droplets. Coughing, sneezing, or even talking can cause droplets of water to enter the air. </li>
                <li>Most droplets fall to the ground, but some can find their way on to the surface of somebody's skin. </li>
                <li>Airborne water droplets can be breathed into the respiratory tract. </li>
                <li>Viral water droplets can contaminate surfaces which people subsequently touch and transfer to their face.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p><strong>What are the consequences of infection?</strong></p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>The coronavirus does not produce symptoms in infected individuals until approximately 5 days after initial contact - but it can range between 2 and 14 days. The rate at which the infection develops is proportional to the level of exposure to the virus. </p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>The infection, by the coronavirus, is called coronavirus disease – Covid-19. The most common symptom people develop is a fever. Nearly 90% of all coronavirus patients report a fever at some point. </p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>Other reported symptoms include a dry scratchy cough, loss of appetite, fatigue, shortness of breath, and many other symptoms reported by less than 20% of cases.</p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p><strong>How does Covid-19 kill?</strong></p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>A healthy immune response to infection is signalled by Cytokines – a chemical in the blood that produces inflammation. This is caused by the release of white blood cells targeting the affected tissues in the body. This increases the blood flow to the infected region causing redness, warmth and decreasing blood pressure. </p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>Some chemicals can leak from inflamed internal tissues causing swelling. This response can cause internal blood clots, most dangerously in the lungs, leading to difficulty breathing.</p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>The virus damages the membrane of infected cells. When alveoli in the lungs are infected this causes their membrane surfaces to harden. Alveoli membranes are thin to allow the diffusion of Oxygen and Carbon Dioxide between the air and the capillaries. </p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>Infected alveoli have a reduced capacity for Oxygen/Carbon Dioxide transport. Collectively, this can significantly impact the efficiency of the lungs, leading to potential death.</p>
